# ============================================================================
# Security Best Practices
# ============================================================================
# 1. Use AWS profiles instead of hardcoded credentials
# 2. Enable MQTT authentication in production
# 3. Enable Redis password protection
# 4. Use SSL/TLS for MQTT and Redis connections
# 5. Set file permissions: chmod 600 .env
# 6. Never commit .env to version control
# 7. Rotate credentials regularly
# 8. Use Kubernetes secrets for sensitive data in production

# ============================================================================
# Troubleshooting
# ============================================================================
# Issue: Services can't connect to S3
# - Check S3_BUCKET exists and credentials are valid
# - Verify ENDPOINT_URL is correct (or commented for AWS)
# - Test: aws s3 ls s3://${S3_BUCKET} --endpoint-url ${ENDPOINT_URL}
#
# Issue: Services can't connect to Kubernetes
# - Verify ~/.kube/config is valid: kubectl get pods
# - Check NRP_NAMESPACE exists: kubectl get namespace
#
# Issue: MQTT connection refused
# - Check MQTT container is running: docker-compose ps mqtt
# - Check MQTT logs: docker-compose logs mqtt
#
# Issue: Redis connection refused  
# - Check Redis container is running: docker-compose ps redis
# - Verify Redis port is not in use: netstat -tuln | grep 6379

# ============================================================================
# Notes
# ============================================================================
# 1. Keep .env file secure - it contains credentials (chmod 600 .env)
# 2. All S3 paths are built from S3_BUCKET + S3_PREFIX automatically
# 3. Services will fail to start if S3_BUCKET is not set
# 4. Use docker-compose config to verify your configuration
# 5. See docker-compose.yml for detailed service documentation
